    "summary": "The Congo Crisis was a period of political turmoil and conflict in the newly independent Democratic Republic of the Congo from 1960 to 1965. When Belgium granted independence in June 1960, the country was almost entirely unprepared for self-governance — Belgium had deliberately limited the education of Congolese people and trained almost no indigenous administrators. Within weeks, the Congolese army mutinied against Belgian officers, Belgian troops intervened, and the mineral-rich Katanga province under Moise Tshombe seceded with Belgian and mining company support.\n\nPrime Minister Patrice Lumumba, the charismatic nationalist leader, appealed to the United Nations and then to the Soviet Union for help retaking Katanga. His overtures to Moscow alarmed the United States and Belgium, who viewed him as a potential communist influence in central Africa. Lumumba was dismissed by President Joseph Kasavubu, arrested by military strongman Joseph Mobutu, and handed over to Katangese authorities, who executed him in January 1961. The assassination, with Western complicity, became a touchstone of anti-colonial grievance.\n\nThe United Nations deployed one of its largest peacekeeping missions to date, but the crisis dragged on through secessionist movements, Soviet-backed factions, and CIA operations. Katanga's secession was ended in 1963. Mobutu staged a final coup in 1965, establishing a decades-long dictatorship. The Congo Crisis illustrated the vulnerability of newly independent African states to Cold War interference and the catastrophic consequences of colonial decolonization without adequate preparation.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congo_Crisis",
